achieved a remarkable synthesis of the huge body of available materials, both primary and secondary.Smelser's latest book will be most controversial in its treatment of class as a primordial social grouping, beyond its economic significance. Indeed, his demonstration that class, ethnic, and religious groupings were decisive in determining the course of British working-class education has broad-ranging implications. These groupings remain at the heart of educational conflict, debate, and change in most societies—including our own—and prompt us to pose again and again the chronic question: who controls the educational terrain?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aEducation, ElementaryxHistoryx19th centuryxGreat BritainxGreat Britain. 0aEducation, ElementaryzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aWorking classxEducationxHistoryx19th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aWorking classxEducationzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  a19th century.  aanglican church.  abritish colonies.  achild labor.  achurch of england.  aclass hierarchy.  aclass system.  acorn laws.  adissenters.  aearly victorian.  aeducation funding.  aeducation reform.  aeducation.  aeducational policy.  aelementary education.  aengland.  afamily life.  agrammar school.  agreat britain.  ahistory.  aireland.  aliteracy.  amass education.  anonfiction.  aprimary education.  apublic education.  apublic schools.  arobert peel.  ascotland.  asecondary education.  asocial change.  avictorian england.  awales.  awhigs.  aworking class education.  aworking class.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091154340uhttps://www.degruyter.